definition.value: An alkane that is hexane substituted by a methyl group at position 3.
A branched alkane that is pentane carrying one methyl group at positions 2, and two methyl groups at position 3.
An alkane that is octane in which the two methylene hydrogens at position 3 have been replaced by methyl groups.
A fatty alcohol that is (3E)-dec-3-ene substituted by a hydroxy group at position 2.
A secondary alcohol that is butan-2-ol in which one of the methyl hydrogen atoms is substituted by chlorine.
A chloroalkane that is 1,3-dichloropropane substituted by a chloro group and a methyl group at position 2.
A member of the class of styrenes that is 1,2-dimethylbenzene substituted by a vinyl group at position 4.
A chloroalkane that is propane substituted by chloro groups at positions 1,1,3 and 3, respectively.
A methyl-branched chain fatty acid that is pent-3-enoic acid substituted by a methyl group at position 4.
A chloroalkane that is butane substituted by chloro groups at positions 1,2,3 and 4.
A glycol that is decane bearing two hydroxy substituents located at positions 1 and 2.
A member of the class of phenols that is phenol substituted by tert-butyl groups at position 2 and 5.
A ribonucleotide residue(1-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group of 5-methoxy-UMP residue; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha-amino-acid cation resulting from the transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of Se-methyl-L-selenomethionine. Major species at pH 7.3

An organofluorine compound that is 1-methyl-6-(trifluoromethyl)pyrimidine-2,4(1H,3H)-dione substituted by a 4-chloro-3-({[2-methyl-1-oxo-1-(prop-2-en-1-yloxy)propan-2-yl]oxy}carbonyl)phenyl group at position 3. It is a herbicide which inhibits the protoporphyrinogen-oxidase enzyme in plant chloroplasts, resulting in rapid knockdown of various broadleaf and grass weeds.
A monocarboxylic acid resulting from the formal 1,4-addition of one of the amino groups of urea to methacrylic acid (the Z isomer), or by the hydrolytic ring cleavage of uracil
A member of the class of xanthones that is 9H-xanthen-9-one substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 1,3 and 8, prenyl groups at positions 2 and 7, and a methyl group at position 4.

A phenanthrene substituted by a 2-(methylamino)ethyl group at position 1 and by methoxy groups at positions 2,3,4,6 and 7, respectively. It is a plant metabolite isolated from Annona purpurea and Fagonia olivieri.
A member of the class of benzaldehydes that is benzaldehyde substituted by an ethoxy group at position 3 and by a (2-methylpropanoyl)oxy group at position 4.

An organic disulfide composed of two molecules of 2-{[2-(1H-indol-3-yl)ethyl]amino}ethane-1-thiol linked together via a disulfide bond. It is a glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) activator which reduces oxidative stress in cells and zebrafish.
A secondary carboxamide that is 2-amino-1-(2-chlorophenyl)ethanol in which one of the amino hydrogens is substituted by a 2-[(2-fluorobenzyl)amino]-2-oxoethyl group.
An isoquinolol that is 1,2,3,4-tetrahydroisoquinolin-4-ol in which the hydrogen of the secondary amine  is substituted by a 3-(3-hydroxy-3-methylbutyl)benzoyl group.
A member of the class pyrazines that is pyrazin-2-amine in which one of the amino protons is substituted by a ({1-[2-(1H-pyrazol-1-yl)phenyl]ethyl}amino)acetyl group.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of N-acetyl-L-tryptophan, obtained by the deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acyl-D-alpha-amino acid anion that is the conjugate base of N-acetyl-D-phenylalanine, arising from the deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An N(2)-acetylglutaminate that has L-configuration; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of N(2)-acetyl-D-glutamine; major species at pH 7.3.
A phosphoethanolamine-GIPC where R1 represents the shingoid base, R2 is an acyl group, R3 can be an acyl group or an H, R4-8 can be other sugar groups, phosphoethanolamine or H.
